Compact, easy-to-grow and adaptable, African violets have been a popular houseplant for generations. Learn how to care for your African violet so it continues to thrive in your home.

content.en-US:
Start by choosing blooms that are just starting to open. Be sure that stems are firm and that petals look healthy. Snip off any leaves that may be damaged or will be submerged in water when the stems are in the vase. Then, in a shallow dish, submerge the stems in water and cut them diagonally with a knife or clippers. Scissors will crush the stems.

Select a vase that has a neck and water reservoir large enough to hold the flowers comfortably. Add a packet of flower food* to lukewarm water in the vase and begin arranging. Insert stems of foliage and filler flowers first. Crisscross the stems as you insert them to form a grid that will hold the other flowers in place. Start at the vase's rim and work toward the center when you add other flowers, placing the longest stems in the center of your arrangement.

*A note about floral food: Floral food is a combination of additives that help nourish the flowers and discourage bacterial growth in the water. Using floral food is one of the best and easiest ways to extend the life of your flowers. It is very important to follow the directions on the package correctly. Improperly mixed floral food can do more harm than good.

For a long-lasting arrangement, choose bouquets with the following flowers:

  • Alstromeria — Five to 10 days in a vase
  • Lilies — Five to 10 days in a vase
  • Carnations — Seven to 14 days in a vase
  • Spray mums — Seven to 14 days in a vase
  • Dendrobium orchids— Five to 10 days in a vase

Trying to raise money for your school, church, or nonprofit organization? Let Bachman's help! As a member of the Twin Cities community for over 130 years, Bachman's is proud to support local organizations like yours through a variety of fundraising programs. So, welcome! We’re so glad you’re here.

## How It Works
There are two avenues for fundraising with Bachman’s: plant sales and gift cards.

### Custom Programs

content.en-US:
People love to embrace autumn’s beauty, so your group will have no problem raising funds when you sell Bachman’s-grown plants. Throughout our 132-year history, we’ve partnered with local organizations to help raise thousands of dollars for local organizations. As a family-owned business, we understand the importance of supporting our community. That’s why we do everything we can to make the administration and fulfillment process easy for you and your team. Your patrons will be thrilled to receive beautiful, Bachman’s-grown plants while supporting your organization.

## Fall Fundraising Program
Reap the benefits of fundraising with Bachman’s! Celebrate the fall harvest and help your community group with a Bachman’s fundraiser.

### How It Works
We provide you with the highest quality Bachman’s product at a discounted rate so you can sell it for a profit during your fundraising drive. Our fall program features our most popular assortment of garden mums, ornamental kale, and purple majesty millet.

First, contact us to let us know your group plans to fundraise with Bachman’s. We’ll provide you with pricing and answers to any questions you may have. Then, promote and sell! This is the time when your group goes out into the community to collect orders. Order forms and product flyers are available for download for your convenience. Lastly, submit your final order form anytime between the start of your fundraising mission and September 14, and select a delivery date. Please allow 10 days for processing between your order submission and your delivery date. (Delivery dates are available from late August through late September, while supplies last.)

That’s it! In no time, you’ll receive the beautiful Bachman’s plants your supporters have ordered and will be able to distribute them.

### Reminders
- Order early for best selection and color mix.
- Orders must be submitted 10 business days prior to the delivery date.
- This program will run through September 14, assuming product is available!

If your group is looking for an easy, year-round opportunity to raise money, Bachman’s Gift Card Fundraising is here to help! The Bachman's Gift Card Program is ready and eager to help nonprofit organizations like yours raise funds for charitable works, church and school activities, and community programs.

## How It Works
The program is simple: Your group sells Bachman's gift cards in amounts from $5 – $500, redeemable in our stores, at Bachmans.com, or through our call center. Buyers can use the gift cards to buy anything they'd like, including a full range of beautiful fresh flowers, plants and shrubs, home décor, holiday gifts, garden items, and more. In return, your group receives 15 percent of your total gift card sales.

Get started in as little as three steps!
1. Fill out the application.
2. Promote and sell! This is the time when your group goes out into the community to collect orders. Order forms are available for download for your convenience.
3. Submit your order form to us. It’ll be a matter of days until your gift cards are ready for distribution.
4. If your organization is interested in learning more about the Bachman's Gift Card Program, or you want to discuss ways that we can tailor the program to fit your group's needs, just ask!

*Please note: The 15 percent rebate is not eligible on gift cards purchased through any of our retail stores or via an alternate department at Bachman's, so make sure to place your order through the appropriate channel.*

The tomato is, by far, the most popular vegetable. It's hard to imagine a garden or a kitchen without them. Learn more about different varieties and how to grow tomatoes in your garden.

content.en-US:
The tomato is, by far, the most popular vegetable in the country (even if it really is a fruit, not a vegetable!) It's hard to imagine a garden or a kitchen without tomatoes. That's pretty amazing, considering they were long thought to be poisonous. But then, they also were considered an aphrodisiac, referred to as "love apples". With the development of new varieties and the rediscovery of many wonderful heirlooms, there probably is a tomato suitable for everyone. Five or six hours of sun each day and water ... that's all that is essential. Even an apartment dweller without a balcony can grow a few tomatoes on a sunny windowsill when choosing a variety like Micro-Tom, the world’s smallest, growing 6-8 inches tall in a 4" pot, bearing miniature fruits the size of croutons. 

### How do I choose what variety of tomato to grow?
The choices can be overwhelming. Here in Minnesota, one of the most important considerations is to choose a tomato that will ripen in our short growing season. Every seed packet or plant tag should indicate the average number of days from the time the tomato is transplanted until you have ripe fruit. Our growing season for tender plants isn't often much longer than 100 days, allowing us to grow early and mid-season varieties. 

### What about the different colors and sizes?
Tomatoes come in almost every color of the rainbow. While you will always want to grow lots of red tomatoes, don't hesitate to tuck in a few that will bear yellow, orange, striped, or even green fruits. Size can vary from bite-size cherries like Sweet 100 to Beefsteaks that weigh in at more than a pound each. 

### Do flavors vary as well?
They sure do. Growing our own tomatoes affords us the luxury of being able to choose the best tasting tomato around, since we don't have to worry about growing a variety that can be picked, handled, stored, shipped and displayed before reaching the table. The varieties offered on seed racks and in garden centers are good tasting tomatoes. If you're looking for a less acid variety, try an orange tomato such as Gold Jubilee. If you want a solid, meaty tomato for slicing, try a Beef Steak. Big Beef does well here, so give it a try. Try a few varieties this season; next season grow your favorite from this year and few others and so on. You won't ever run out of choices! 

### What are heirloom tomatoes?
To be considered an heirloom, a variety should have been around at least 50 years and be open pollinated. To be kept that long, the tomato is bound to have some wonderful attributes. Some become heirloom because they produce so well, others because they are disease resistant and others because of their flavor. The variety Brandywine, an Amish heirloom since 1885, is legendary for its rich flavor. 

### Should I start my tomatoes from seed or buy the plants?
If you have enough light and room indoors, it can be fun and rewarding to start your own tomatoes. Starting your own also gives you the opportunity to grow varieties that may not be available as plants. On the other hand, we offer a wide variety of great looking tomato plants at affordable prices that you can take right home and tuck in the garden. 

### Can I grow my tomatoes in containers?
Tomatoes are well suited to container gardening. If you don't have room for a large plant that will need staking or cages, choose a bush variety. Containers can vary from buckets, to barrels to bathtubs. Try growing several varieties of tomatoes together in a half-barrel; they will do great as long as it isn't crowded by other plants around the container. 

### What do they mean by determinate and indeterminate?
A determinate tomato plant will grow to a certain size and stop, bearing most of its fruit in a short period of 2-4 weeks. Determinate tomatoes are great for canning or smaller spaces. A few determinate tomatoes are large enough to need support, but most of them can grow without stakes or cages. Indeterminate tomatoes just keep on growing and bearing fruit. They will need support and continually bloom and fruit. 

### Does it make any difference if the variety is open pollinated?
Whether a plant is open pollinated or hybrid matters only if you are saving the seeds from year to year. Hybrids are usually more vigorous and prolific. 

### What is the earliest I can safely plant a tomato?
Tomatoes are very sensitive to cold and cannot tolerate even a light frost, especially when they are coming out of a greenhouse or warm home. Traditionally, Memorial Day weekend is the safe date, but most people try to sneak in a few a week or two earlier. 

### I saw an ad for the Wall of Water ... do they work?
As crazy as they sound and look, the product does help. The water filling the walls acts as an insulator, giving your tomato plants a much better chance of surviving a light frost undamaged. 

### Once I have them planted, how should I care for my tomatoes?
They will do best with a consistent supply of water, preferably provided from below the foliage. When tomato plants are water stressed, they are more susceptible to diseases. Water stress also contributes to blossom end rot and fruit cracking. 

### Is it really necessary to use wire cages or stakes?
With indeterminate tomatoes that just keep on growing, it is hard to manage the plant without some type of support. Allowing the plants to sprawl makes it much harder to keep them clean and undamaged, leading to disease. You can cut back the leader of the plant to limit it's height, but it may impact on the amount of fruit it produces. 

### I saw a product called Blossom Set ... will I need to use it to get tomatoes?
Blossom Set is a good idea if your tomatoes are the only ones growing in the immediate area or if the weather is so cool that there aren't very many insects to help pollinate the plants. 

### How soon can I expect ripe tomatoes?
This will vary according to the variety, temperatures, amount of sun and general care. 

### I've had problems in the past with diseases in tomatoes ... is there anything I can do to avoid it this season?
There are several things you can do culturally to help. Keep your tomatoes as evenly watered as possible, water from below, apply plenty of mulch, avoid growing tomatoes where you have had problems before and choose varieties resistant to diseases. 

### What about insects and slugs?
Tomatoes are a favorite of aphids and slugs. Watch the new foliage for insects and spray with insecticidal soap. Slugs can be discouraged by mulching with a coarse material (such as diatomaceous earth, sand or sharp gravel) or you can use baits and traps.

Losing a loved one is a difficult experience and offers a time and place to come together to commemorate their special life. We recognize the challenges of this difficult time and are here to help you through the process of ordering and sending expressions of sympathy. We hope to help you as best as we can by providing useful information about floral etiquette for funerals, different cultural practices, and offering you beautiful ideas that pay tribute to your loved one and express compassionate support for remaining family and friends.

Please accept our sincere condolences for your loss.

At Bachman’s, we’re here to help you through this difficult time by arranging all of your floral needs—whether you’re a close relative or friend of the deceased. We offer a variety of floral arrangements, expressions of sympathy, and memorial baskets.

The first step to ordering floral arrangements for the funeral service or visitation or sending floral arrangements to the family of the deceased as a friend is to understand the proper etiquette of doing so.


## Sympathy Flowers: Etiquette and Responsibility

__Family__

- Burial Floral Arrangements: Burials traditionally include sprays to be placed on a casket, insets, and wreaths and other blooms on easels.

- Family members usually order the casket spray and any flowers to be placed inside the casket. Additional fresh flowers, easel arrangements, and European baskets (including both green and blooming plants), and other flowers are often added by family members.

- Memorial Floral Arrangements: Memorials typically feature an urn and memory piece surrounded by flowers or flanked with fresh accents.

- Family members usually order any flowers to be placed around the urn or memory piece. Additional fresh flowers, easel arrangements, and European baskets (including both green and blooming plants), and other flowers are often added by family members.

__Friends__

- Groups or individuals close to the deceased or family members often send their own arrangements as well. You may bring flowers directly to the funeral home, but give the bouquet or arrangement to the funeral director for proper placement. Include your first and last name in the enclosure card. If sending from a group, you can include each individual’s name or simply the group name, like “Book Club.” Include at least one contact name so that a thank you card can be sent.

- Fresh arrangements, baskets, planters, green and blooming plants, and other remembrance gifts are often welcome. You may bring flowers directly to the funeral home, but give the bouquet or arrangement to the funeral director for proper placement. Include your first and last name in the enclosure card. If sending from a group, you can include each individual’s name or simply the group name, like “Book Club.” Include at least one contact name so that a thank you card can be sent.

#### Some common sentiments to write inside of an enclosure card include:

*“Our prayers are with you.”*

*“Our thoughts and prayers are with you.”*

*“Peace and comfort.”*

*“Peace of the Lord be with you.”*

*“Please accept my condolences.”*

*“You have my deepest sympathy.”*


#### Other Sympathy Resources
###### Cultural Sensitivity | Memory Motifs | Sympathy FAQs | Terminology

description.en-US: The first step to ordering floral arrangements for the funeral service or visitation or sending floral arrangements to the family of the deceased is to understand the proper etiquette of doing so.

content.en-US:
## Some Key Words Defined

__Visitation (also known as prayer service, reviewal, or wake):__ Usually held at a funeral home the evening before the funeral service, where friends and family may meet with the family of the deceased and extend their condolences.

__Service:__ Usually held immediately or a day after the visitation. It may be held at a church, funeral home, memorial chapel, or gravesite.

__Banner (also known as a Ribbon, Sash, or Script):__ Gold lettering (block print) written on a ribbon, expressing the relationship of the deceased to the sender. For example, “Mother,” “Wife,” “Sister,” or “Grandmother.”

__Casket Spray:__ An arrangement of flowers placed on a casket.

__Easel:__ A frame, usually 3-legged, made of wood, metal, or branches that displays and supports sympathy pieces. Arrangements designed for easel display can be a spray, wreath, cross, heart, and/or free-form shapes.

__Pedestal:__ Flowers designed as a 3-sided arrangement to be displayed on a pedestal.

__Basket:__ Arrangement of green and blooming plants in various styles of baskets. A basket offers a lovely alternative in floral memorials and may easily be divided following the service for family members to each take home a plant.

__Inset:__ A cluster of flowers placed inside the casket, often a tribute from the grandchildren or a particular group.

__Urn Arrangement:__ Designed to surround or complement a cremation urn or box. Please provide vessel dimensions so that the design can be appropriately sized.

__Vase Arrangement:__ A vessel made of glass, porcelain, earthenware, or metal, usually higher than it is wide, used to hold cut, arranged flowers.

__Personalize or Honoring Loved One:__ It is important to acknowledge the unique personality of your loved one by capturing their persona, momentous occations, milestones, or their life's journey. If you have a special keepsake or memento of your loved one, we invite you to work one-on-one with our sales consultants to create a floral arrangement that is truly unqiue.

description.en-US: Understand the variety of sympathy arrangements available and what each is often used for in a service or memorial.

Each culture has its own traditions, rituals, and ways of expressing grief and mourning. Although not comprehensive, the following information provides some of the funeral and mourning practices within our region.

__Asian:__ Mourning can take anywhere from 7 – 49 days, and there are many traditions. Services are usually held in a family home. Red is seen as a happy color, so should not be included, unless requested. White or yellow are acceptable. The traditional flowers of grief in most Asian countries are chrysanthemums. Lotus flowers are also recommended. Flowers and food are often placed near the casket during the funeral services. Cremations are rare.

__Buddhist:__ White flowers are traditional. Skip red, as it can be considered distasteful. It’s advised to contact the family before sending flowers, as they may not be encouraged. Visiting is okay after the services, but not before. Also do not send food to the family.

__Hindu:__ Cremation usually takes place within 24 hours and a priest and family members conduct services. Families order flower garlands and sprays that are placed in the casket, but mourners should not bring flowers or anything else to the service. Traditionally, people gather at the family home 10 days after the funeral, and mourners are expected to bring fruit to this ceremony (fruit baskets recommended), but no flowers or other gifts.

__Hispanic:__ Similar to the Roman Catholic religion, respectable and somber floral arrangements are recommended, with saints, Mary, or cross symbolism incorporated. Flower arrangements, wreaths, and plants are acceptable gifts to send to the funeral home, church, and the family home.

__Hmong:__ Due to varying opinions and traditions, it’s best to ask the family.

__Jewish:__ The burial takes place within 24 hours, so flowers are not part of the services and should not be sent to the synagogue or family home. Charitable donations are preferred as expressions of sympathy. A green plant, blooming plant, or fruit basket can be sent to the home with a “Thinking of You” enclosure. After the burial, the family sits in mourning for 7 days, called Shiva. It’s customary for friends and relatives to visit the home during this time and bring food baskets with kosher items, fruit, desserts, and drinks.

__Mormon (Church of Jesus Christ or Latter-Day Saints):__ Floral tributes can be sent to the services or the family home. Do not include a crucifix or anything in the shape of a cross.

__Muslim:__ There are varying opinions regarding sending flowers, so it’s best to ask the family. Fruit baskets are welcome to bring to the family home following the services.

__Protestant (Baptist, Episcopalian, Lutheran, Methodist, and Presbyterian):__ Sending flowers to the funeral home or the family home is appropriate. You can also send a card and/or other expression of your sympathy, like a small statue or symbolic gift. Bringing food to the family home is also welcome.

__Roman Catholic:__ Flowers are often an important part of the ritual. Before the funeral service, a vigil or wake is held with floral arrangements and green and blooming plants to decorate the area. Flowers are also present during the service and at the burial site. Traditional arrangements, often with the addition of saints, Mary, or cross symbolism, can be sent to the funeral home, church, and/or family home. Cards, angel statues, crosses, and other remembrance mementos are welcome.

description.en-US: Each culture has its own traditions, rituals, and ways of expressing grief and mourning. Learn more from Bachman's about the funeral and mourning practices within our region.

When you partner with Bachman’s, you can expect outstanding service and exceptional quality as we bring beauty and inspiration to your indoor space.

We offer a multitude of services to meet our clients' needs. Our design team can help you decide which services are right for you. Our services include live and artificial plant displays, professional installation services, holiday decorating, and plant maintenance.

__Live & Artificial Plants__

Live plants: Find the perfect, fresh accent for your indoor space from our large selection of plants. Our designers will help you select plant varieties that fit your aesthetic and the correct light requirements for each location.
Blooming plants: We bring splashes of color to your establishment on a regular basis to brighten up your space.
Permanent flowers and plants: For areas where greenery won’t thrive or cannot be easily maintained, permanent flowers and plants provide long-lasting style and look as natural as the real thing.
Indoor containers: Our vast selection of containers offer a solution for every style, from traditional to contemporary and everything in between.

__Installation__

Live and moss walls: This unique trend is quite avant-garde and puts the skills of our designers to the test as they create a botanical work of art that will—literally—bring your space to life.

__Holiday Decorating__

When it’s time to get into the holiday spirit, we’ll transform your everyday space into a winter wonderland. Our design team uses current trends to make your décor stand out in preparation for holiday parties or to simply spread some holiday cheer.

__Maintenance__

Keeping live plants looking their best is part science, part art. After we install your plants, our horticulture maintenance staff will carefully tend to your plants, keeping them healthy and beautiful. As true masters of horticulture, our mission is to provide exceptional service while maintaining high standards for each of our clients.

__Plants-at-Work__

Plants in the workplace offer more than aesthetic value. In fact, studies have shown they help reduce stress, enhance employee attitudes, increase productivity, and improve air quality. Work with our talented team of designers to create spaces to connect with nature and provide healthy and productive environments.

Personalization allows your own style and tastes to shine through in your floral arrangements. Some common ways to personalize your wedding flowers include monograms throughout the ceremony and reception, petals down the aisle in monogram form, monogram letters covered in flowers to hang from the ceremony door or on reception tables, monograms or pictures added to centerpieces, photos of loved ones added to the bride’s bouquet, using Mom’s or Grandma’s wedding dress to wrap the bouquet or boutonnieres, and adding broaches or jewelry to bouquets or boutonnieres. The possibilities are endless; we’d love to work with you to make your wedding arrangements truly special!
Varying shades of green in bouquets and centerpieces convey earthy tones and pops of color.
Blue is an elegant floral choice; mixed with white flowers, blue arrangements can create beautiful bouquets and centerpieces.
Dark purple mixed with hints of pastel creates a fun and striking color palette.

Brilliant primaries can energize floral features with a bold palette or highlight key floral details. If you are hesitant about choosing a bold hue for an entire bouquet or arrangement, try strategic pops of color.
White and ivory colored arrangements are the classic choice that offer a type of serene elegance.
Pink floral arrangements are ultra feminine and help cultivate a fun and vibrant atmosphere.
Jillian and Calvin chose to take it simple and elegant, with bouquets in varying shades of white and cream.
Amanda wanted tone-on-tone floral arrangements for her wedding, which resulted in beautiful, vibrant, monochromatic bouquets.
Madi and Chace desired a more natural and organic look for their floral bouquets and were pleased with the variety of unique plants we were able to incorporate.
We were able to capture Lauren's unique style with organic floral arrangements blooming with color and intrigue.
Lee and Eric got married in the fall and wanted to capture the beauty of the season in their floral choices; their bouquets and arrangements were full of life and color.

Bachman’s delivers over 200 packages per day in their fleet of purple trucks.

### Delivery Times
Orders received by 11:00 a.m. Monday – Saturday CST can be delivered in our delivery area by 5 p.m. CST.  We do not deliver on Sundays.

Orders received before noon CST the day before delivery have the option to choose morning delivery (9 a.m. – 1 p.m.), afternoon delivery (1 p.m. – 5 p.m.), or no preference.

Funeral orders can be delivered for services beginning at 10 a.m. CST or later.  If delivery is required before 10 a.m., we will deliver the day prior to the service.

In the case of inclement weather, we may need to adjust our delivery times and availability.

### Delivery Rates

- Our standard delivery fee is $12.99*.
- Funeral and church delivery is $12.99.
- Cemetery delivery is $15.99.
- Wire service out-of-town rates vary. Please call the Order Center at (612) 861-7311 for specific information.
**For some items, a handling fee will apply.*

### Handling Fees

Some items require extra people, equipment, or care for successful delivery.  For these items, a handling fee will apply.

Items requiring a handling fee include:

- Fresh design, delivery of 50 or more items to one location
- Annuals and perennials, delivery of 50 or more items to one location
- Trees
- Evergreens
- Shrubs
- B&B trees
- Christmas trees
- Patio furniture
- Pottery, fountains and statuary
- Gazebos and arbors
- Bagged soils, mulches, and straw
- Raised gardens
- Fire pits

### Delivery Locations

We deliver to cities surrounding our stores in the Minneapolis/St. Paul area. For a list of cities we deliver to, please see the Delivery FAQ’s.

We also offer nationwide delivery for cities outside of our local delivery area through wire services.

Many of our wonderful gift products can be shipped nationwide via UPS.  This includes our Signature Watch 'em Grow™ bulb gardens, gift products, some grills and patio furniture, and gift cards.

For additional delivery information, please see the Delivery FAQ’s or contact the Order Center at (612) 861-7311.
